					<head>Majmu'ah</head>
					<msContents class="#multipleWorks">
						<summary>A selection of Persian verse and prose lore, most if not all of which is Sufi-influenced. The five texts are attributed, tenuously for the most part, to a number of renowned figures. The rarity and interest of this manuscript lies in its originating from Central Asia (East Turkistan) or possibly from China, and in its bold and distinctive, if unsophisticated, ornamentation. </summary>
						<msItem n="1" xml:id="a1" class="http://id.loc.gov/authorities/sh85100085 http://id.loc.gov/authorities/sh85109764">
							<locus from="1v" to="6v">ff 1v-6v</locus>
							<author ref="http://lccn.loc.gov/n79105787">
								<persName xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc" type="supplied"
									key="http://lccn.loc.gov/n79105787">Omar Khayyam</persName>
								<persName xml:lang="per" key="http://lccn.loc.gov/n79105787"
									type="supplied">عمر خیام</persName>
							</author>
							<locus n=""/>
							<title xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc">Rubāʻīyāt-i ʻUmar Khayyām</title>
							<title xml:lang="per">رباعيات عمر خيام</title>
							<note>
								<p>Quatrains traditionally attributed to ‘Umar Khayyām or Khayyāmī
									(d. 517/1123).The verses are punctuated on f. 5v by an anecdote
									about the renowned Sufi Bayazīd Basṭāmī and a man who claimed to
									have the cure for every ill. </p>
							</note>
